// Egyptian Gods — the canonical 12 deities of the Two Lands — SEO funnel.
// /gab44/egyptian-gods (index) + /gab44/egyptian-gods/{slug}.
//
// Peer to Olympians, Norse Gods, and Hindu Devas. Closes the most-searched
// remaining mythology gap on gab44 — Egyptian funerary religion is the
// highest-emotional-intent surface in all of comparative mythology because
// it explicitly addresses the death-rebirth crossing (Anubis at the scales,
// Isis in grief, Osiris in the afterlife, Ma'at in the weighing of the heart).
//
// Three-family taxonomy:
//  - Solar court (Ra, Horus, Hathor, Sekhmet) — sun-gold/coral; the royal
//    sun-cycle, kingship, the eye-of-Ra register.
//  - Osirian cycle (Osiris, Isis, Anubis, Set) — black-jade-lapis; the
//    death-and-resurrection myth that anchored Egyptian funerary practice
//    for three thousand years.
//  - Memphite & Hermopolitan (Ptah, Thoth, Ma'at, Bastet) — turquoise/silver;
//    creator-craftsman, wisdom-scribe, cosmic-order, and joy-protection.
//
// Source-honest from the Pyramid Texts (c. 2400-2300 BCE, Old Kingdom), the
// Coffin Texts (c. 2100-1800 BCE, Middle Kingdom), the Book of the Dead
// (the Papyrus of Ani, c. 1250 BCE), the Hymn to Osiris (Stela of Amenmose),
// Plutarch's De Iside et Osiride (c. 100 CE — the single most-cited Greek
// account of Osiris-Isis), Herodotus Histories Book 2 (c. 440 BCE), the
// Memphite Theology (Shabaka Stone c. 700 BCE recording older material),
// Apuleius Metamorphoses 11 (the Isis-initiation, c. 170 CE).
// Shadow-honest: 19th-c. Egyptomania and racial-erasure of African Egypt,
// the Aleister-Crowley Thelemic appropriation of Horus, the Hollywood-
// Anubis-as-villain (The Mummy 1999/2001/2008), the New-Age commodification
// of Isis, the white-nationalist co-option of Set as "European-pagan" deity.

