    meaning: 'Ra (rꜥ — "sun") is the chief deity of Heliopolis (the city of On, modern Cairo suburb of el-Matariya), the self-created creator-god of one of the oldest Egyptian theological systems (the Heliopolitan Ennead, attested in the Pyramid Texts c. 2400 BCE but probably older). In the Heliopolitan cosmogony, *Atum* emerges from the primordial waters of Nun, creates himself, and then through masturbation or breath produces *Shu* (air) and *Tefnut* (moisture), who in turn produce *Geb* (earth) and *Nut* (sky), who in turn produce Osiris, Isis, Set, and Nephthys. Atum-Ra is the unified creator-and-sun-god — *Atum* at the evening of self-creation, *Ra* at the midday of full power, *Khepri* (the scarab-beetle) at the dawn of rebirth. The solar barque (the *Mandjet* by day, the *Mesektet* by night) carries Ra across the sky and through the duat (underworld). At the seventh hour of the night Ra must fight *Apophis* (Apep), the cosmic chaos-serpent who tries to swallow the sun — the daily battle that the morning sunrise confirms Ra has won. The pharaoh from the Old Kingdom forward was *son of Ra* (sꜣ-rꜥ), a title that became part of the royal titulary. Akhenaten (c. 1353-1336 BCE) attempted to replace the entire Egyptian pantheon with the worship of a single solar disk, *Aten*, in what is sometimes called the first monotheistic experiment — abandoned after his death. The *eye of Ra* is a distinct theological motif: the goddess (most often Hathor or Sekhmet, sometimes Bastet, Wadjet, Mut) who is sent forth as Ra\'s fierce manifestation and who must be soothed and brought back. The Greek-Roman period syncretized Ra with Helios.',
