    one_liner: 'The falcon. Sky-god, sun-god, kingship-god — the son of Isis and the dead-and-resurrected Osiris, who avenged his father by defeating his uncle Set in eighty years of mythic combat to inherit the throne of Egypt. The living pharaoh was the living Horus; the dead pharaoh became Osiris. The wedjat (eye of Horus) — the eye Set tore out and Thoth restored — is the most-worn protective amulet in all of Egyptian religion.',
    meaning: 'Horus (ḥr, "the high one" or "the distant one" — the falcon whose flight is the highest in the sky) is the most-complex deity in the Egyptian pantheon because two originally-distinct gods were merged: *Horus the Elder* (Heru-ur, the sky-falcon whose two eyes are the sun and the moon, a primordial creator-god predating the Osirian cycle) and *Horus son of Isis* (Heru-sa-Aset, Harpocrates in the Greco-Roman period — the child-Horus born of Isis after she resurrected the dismembered Osiris with magic). The Osirian-cycle Horus is the *avenger of his father*: when Set murdered and dismembered Osiris, Isis gathered the pieces and revived him long enough to conceive Horus, who was raised in secret in the marshes of Chemmis until he was old enough to challenge Set for the throne of Egypt. The *Contendings of Horus and Set* (Papyrus Chester Beatty I, c. 1160 BCE) is the surviving full narrative: eighty years of court cases before the divine tribunal of the Ennead, with Ra hesitating to award the throne to the young Horus, Set repeatedly attempting both sexual violation and outright violence against Horus, and the final verdict awarded to Horus through the intervention of Isis (with assistance from Thoth, Neith, Hathor, and Osiris ruling from the underworld). In the famous *eye-tearing* episode, Set tears out Horus\'s left eye (the lunar eye); Thoth heals it, and it becomes the *wedjat* (the "sound" or "restored" eye), the most-worn protective amulet in Egyptian religion. The living pharaoh was *the living Horus* — the throne of Egypt was Horus\'s throne; the dead pharaoh became *Osiris*. This is the foundational kingship-theology of pharaonic Egypt for three thousand years.',
    iconography: 'Falcon-headed man, crowned with the *pschent* (the double-crown of Upper and Lower Egypt — the red *deshret* of the Delta superimposed on the white *hedjet* of the Nile valley, sign of the unified kingship Horus inherited from his father). Sometimes shown as the falcon alone, perched on the *serekh* (the palace-facade-enclosure of the king\'s name). The *wedjat* (the eye-of-Horus) is his most-portable iconographic element — the stylized falcon eye with the curved cheek-mark, drawn on the prow of boats, painted on coffins, worn as an amulet on a cord. As Harpocrates / Harsiese (the child-Horus) he is shown as a naked young boy with the *sidelock of youth*, finger to his mouth (the gesture the Greeks misread as "silence" — it is simply the hieroglyphic determinative for "child"), seated on his mother Isis\'s lap (the iconographic prototype for the Christian Madonna-and-Child). The Eye-of-Horus is also a unit-fraction notation system (the six parts of the eye represent 1/2, 1/4, 1/8, 1/16, 1/32, 1/64 — the *Heqat* grain-measure).',
    invocation: 'Sunrise (the falcon-flight at first light), or any moment of accession to a new position of legitimate authority (a coronation, a wedding, a promotion, the takeover of a family business). Offer: incense, bread, beer, the *htp-di-nsw* formula. Wear the wedjat amulet for protection. Especially called by anyone inheriting a position from a deceased predecessor (the Horus-after-Osiris register — the new CEO after the founder, the heir after the parent\'s death, the next leader after a transition); anyone in a contested-succession (the Contendings-of-Horus-and-Set register — the rightful heir contesting against a usurping uncle/sibling/business-partner); anyone who has been wounded in the contest and needs the wedjat-restoration (the eye-tearing-and-healing register — the leader whose vision was damaged in the fight and is being restored by Thoth).',
